                <p/>
 </div><div type="translation" xml:lang="fr" xml:space="preserve">
            <p><gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"/> sans <gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"/> conformément aux <gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"/> dont ils ont délibéré <gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"/> vers/ en rapport avec cela <gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"/>  des dieux <gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"/>.</p>
         </div><div type="translation" xml:lang="en" xml:space="preserve">
            <p> <gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"/> without <gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"/> following the <gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"/> about which they have deliberated <gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"/> regarding those matters <gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"/>  of the gods <gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"/>.</p>
         </div><div type="translation" xml:lang="it" xml:space="preserve">
            <p><gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"/> senza <gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"/> conformemente a <gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"/> su cui hanno deliberato <gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"/> riguardo queste faccende <gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"/> degli dèi <gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"/>.</p>
            </div><div type="commentary">
                
                <p>Because a part is lost, it cannot be decided whether <ref type="inscription" source="#IGCyr2">IGCyr062840</ref> is the beginning
                    of the same document or of a different one; anyway this is again a text in koine
                    and should come from the Ptolemaic authorities.</p>
                <p>The gods mentioned at l. 9 may be either traditional Greek gods or the divinised
                    royals.</p>
                <p>The inventory numbers show that at least some parts of the stone were already in the epigraphic collection at the time of the reorganization of the Cyrenaean antiquities 
                    after World War II care of Goodchild (from 1956 on) and before Fraser observed one of them. They were perhaps all found during the Italian period, like both fragments of 
                    <ref type="inscription" source="#IGCyr2">IGCyr062830</ref>.</p>
            </div></body>
